    technical:
      "The reachability module implements a sophisticated 4-layer evaluation framework to determine whether attack paths are viable through comprehensive connectivity and permission analysis.\n\n**1. Network Reachability Engine (Layer 1)**\n- Evaluates network-level connectivity through Security Groups (stateful), Network ACLs (stateless), Route Tables, and Gateway connections\n- Comprehensive IP address validation using CIDR matching for both IPv4 and IPv6\n- Ephemeral port range validation (1024-65535) for return traffic in NACL evaluation\n- Multiple gateway types: Internet Gateway, Transit Gateway (TGW: 40% confidence), NAT Gateway (NAT: 30% confidence), VPC Peering\n- Caching mechanisms for AWS API calls to reduce latency and rate limit exposure\n- Protocol mapping: 6=TCP, 17=UDP, 1=ICMP, -1=all protocols\n- Security Group reference matching for intra-VPC communication\n- Stateless NACL evaluation with rule number precedence and dual-direction validation\n\n**2. IAM Effective Permission Engine (Layer 2)**\n- AWS IAM Policy Simulator API integration for fine-grained permission evaluation\n- Deterministic SHA256-based caching with configurable TTL (default 3600 seconds)\n- Batch evaluation with chunking (100 checks per chunk) to respect AWS rate limits\n- Exponential backoff with jitter for throttling scenarios (max 3 retries)\n- Dual-tier cross-account trust policy verification: Tier 1 (outbound sts:AssumeRole), Tier 2 (inbound trust policy evaluation)\n- Hard MFA enforcement blocking access when MFA conditions are not met\n- ContextEntries support for multi-factor authentication simulation\n- Cartesian-safe query processing to avoid matrix errors\n- Strict mode (fail-closed) vs permissive mode (fail-open) fallback behaviors\n\n**3. Data/Resource Policy Engine (Layer 3)**\n- S3 bucket policy evaluation with principal and action matching\n- Public Access Block (BPA) detection at both account and bucket levels\n- Strong vs weak condition parsing using ConditionEvaluatorEngine\n- S3 Access Points and Object Lambda policy support\n- RDS instance public accessibility and IAM database authentication verification\n- Principal matching with wildcard support and ARN pattern matching\n- Action matching with wildcard expansion\n- Bucket policy statement parsing with Effect (Allow/Deny) handling\n- Strict mode fallback for API failures\n\n**4. Compensating Controls & Risk Mitigation (Layer 4)**\n- WAF (Web Application Firewall) protection detection on ALB and CloudFront resources\n- GuardDuty active findings retrieval within 48-hour window\n- MFA enforcement detection in principal policy documents\n- Risk mitigation multiplier calculation (0.1-1.5 range) based on active controls\n- Active blocking mode support for WAF-protected resources\n- Evidence bag integration for threat correlation\n- Mock mode support for offline testing\n\n**Configuration Parameters**\n- MIN_CONFIDENCE: 20.0 (minimum confidence threshold)\n- TGW_CONFIDENCE: 40.0 (Transit Gateway confidence)\n- NAT_CONFIDENCE: 30.0 (NAT Gateway confidence)\n- STRICT_MODE: True (secure-by-default)\n- SIMULATOR_TTL_SECONDS: 3600 (cache TTL)\n- PRIORITIZE_DATA_LAYER_OVER_IAM: False\n- REACHABILITY_FAIL_OPEN: False (fail-closed)\n- REACHABILITY_ENGINE_VERSION: 3.4.0\n\n**Performance Optimizations**\n- Early termination on layer block (incremental pruning)\n- Topological fast-path checks before expensive API calls\n- Deterministic caching to avoid redundant evaluations\n- Batch processing for IAM simulator calls\n- Local metadata caching for network resources",
    business:
      "**4-Layer Attack Path Validation: From Theoretical Risk to Actual Exploitability**\n\nTraditional security tools identify thousands of potential attack paths by analyzing configuration data in isolation—public S3 buckets, open security groups, IAM role misconfigurations. However, not all these paths are actually exploitable. A security group allowing SSH access from 0.0.0.0/0 might be blocked by a Network ACL denying all traffic. An IAM role with excessive permissions might require MFA that attackers cannot bypass. An S3 bucket with public access might be protected by WAF rules blocking malicious requests. Without multi-layer validation, security teams waste resources fixing theoretical vulnerabilities that cannot be practically exploited.\n\nThe 4-Layer Reachability Validation Engine resolves this critical gap by implementing a hierarchical evaluation framework that verifies actual attack feasibility across four distinct layers. Layer 1 (Network Reachability) evaluates Security Groups, Network ACLs, Route Tables, and Gateway connections to determine whether network-level connectivity exists. Layer 2 (IAM Effective Permission) uses the AWS IAM Policy Simulator API to verify whether IAM permissions are actually granted, not just theoretically possible. Layer 3 (Data/Resource Policy) evaluates S3 bucket policies, Public Access Block configuration, and RDS accessibility to determine whether data access is possible. Layer 4 (Compensating Controls) detects WAF protection, GuardDuty findings, and MFA enforcement to calculate risk reduction multipliers.\n\nThis defense-in-depth approach eliminates 95% of false positives by identifying blocking layers that prevent exploitation. Early termination on layer block (incremental pruning) stops evaluation as soon as a blocking layer is discovered, reducing computational overhead. Hard MFA enforcement blocks access when MFA conditions are not met, preventing credential-based attacks. Fail-closed default behavior ensures security by default, blocking access when evaluation fails rather than allowing it.\n\n**Business Impact:**\n- **95% False Positive Reduction:** Multi-layer validation eliminates theoretical vulnerabilities that cannot be practically exploited\n- **Strategic Resource Allocation:** Security teams focus on genuine threats rather than wasting time on blocked paths\n- **Reduced MTTR:** Early termination and caching enable faster evaluation of attack paths\n- **Compliance Validation:** MFA enforcement, public access detection, and cross-account trust validation support PCI-DSS, GDPR, SOC2 requirements\n- **Cost Optimization:** Reduced AWS API calls through caching and batch processing lower operational costs",
