    business:
      "**Autonomous Red Teaming: Prove Exploitability Before Attackers Do**\n\nTraditional security tools identify thousands of theoretical attack paths by analyzing configuration data in isolation—public S3 buckets, open security groups, IAM role misconfigurations. However, not all these paths are actually exploitable. A security group allowing SSH access from 0.0.0.0/0 might be blocked by a Network ACL denying all traffic. An IAM role with excessive permissions might require MFA that attackers cannot bypass. An S3 bucket with public access might be protected by WAF rules blocking malicious requests. Without real-world validation, security teams waste resources fixing theoretical vulnerabilities that cannot be practically exploited.\n\nThe Autonomous Red Teaming & Attack Path Validation module resolves this critical gap by implementing two distinct simulation modes: Deep Dry-Run mode with real AWS API evidence collection and Semantic mode with narrative-based offline estimation. The EvidenceCollector performs live API validation across 7 resource types (EC2, S3, RDS, IAM, Security Groups, ALB/NLB, ElastiCache) with cross-region fallback and adaptive retry. For EC2 instances, it collects instance state, public IP status (HIGH RISK if present), IMDSv2 configuration (HIGH RISK if optional), IAM role attachment, and EBS encryption status. For S3 buckets, it evaluates Public Access Block configuration (CRITICAL if not fully enabled), default encryption (HIGH RISK if None), bucket policy (HIGH RISK if custom), and bucket ACL (CRITICAL if public read/write).\n\nThe AutonomousBreachEngine delivers intelligent confidence scoring with deterministic formulas based on graph metadata. Evidence weight is 90% if the node is in the graph, 70% otherwise. Path hops factor is calculated as max(10, 40 - (path_length * 5)). The confidence formula combines evidence weight (60%), path hops factor (30%), and a base confidence of 10%. MITRE ATT&CK mapping provides 12 technique mappings including TA0010 (Data Exfiltration), TA0006 (Credential Access), T1552.005 (Cloud Instance Metadata API), T1190 (Exploit Public-Facing Application), and T1210 (Exploitation of Remote Services).\n\nThe module's read-only approach ensures safe production use without triggering GuardDuty alerts. All API calls are read-only with no resource modification. Credential validation includes STS identity verification, IAM simulator integration, and pre-flight permission checks. The module successfully bridges the gap between theoretical attack paths and practical exploitability validation, providing security teams with actionable intelligence for prioritization and remediation.\n\n**Business Impact:**\n- **Theoretical to Practical Validation:** Proves exploitability of theoretical attack paths through real AWS API evidence collection\n- **Safe Production Use:** Read-only API calls ensure no GuardDuty alerts triggered, no resource modification\n- **Intelligent Confidence Scoring:** Deterministic formulas based on graph metadata provide reliable exploitability assessment\n- **MITRE ATT&CK Integration:** 12 technique mappings enable threat actor association and executive reporting\n- **Resource Coverage:** 7 resource types (EC2, S3, RDS, IAM, Security Groups, ALB/NLB, ElastiCache) with cross-region fallback",
